<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by The Detention Forum (LAI 0047)</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Detention Forum is a network of NGOs, faith groups and others, working together to question the use of detention in the UK immigration system.  In this document, we provid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e our view</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> on the proposed resident test only.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Although we do not provide </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">comments on the other proposals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, that should not be taken as indication that we agree with the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In our response to the Transforming Legal Aid consultation in June this year, we strongly opposed the introduction of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">residence test.  While we welcome </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ex</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">em</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ptions to the test announced by the Ministry of Justice on 5 September 2013</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, we remain convinced that the proposal, unless dropped altogether, will destroy the rule of law and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">undermine</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> fundamental mechanism that safeguards human rights in the UK.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The ex</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">em</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ptions provide civil legal aid for only some exceptional cases: asylum</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> seekers while their asylum claims are pending, including legal aid for making fresh claims, immigration detainees but only for cases that engage the issue of liberty (bail, unlawful detention and so on), some children if the case is about child protection</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, victims of trafficking, domestic violence and forced marriages if they are recognized as victims and only for specific types of cases.   </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As a result, taken together, the proposed residence test will still remove from the scope of civil legal aid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a siza</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ble population </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a wide range of situations where their human rights are violated.  The Office of National Statistics estimates there were between 300,000 and 570,000 undocumented migrants in the UK in 2005</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  Their irregular immigration status means that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> they are not allowed to work, and if they are in work, they are likely to be receiving low wages in informal economy, potentially in an exploitative situation.  In our view, it is unlikely that they are able to afford </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">private </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">legal advice and representati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which makes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">vital that legal aid continues to be available for everyone.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The residence test, even with the ex</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">em</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ptions, still den</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> access to civil legal aid for the following types of individuals and cases:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Anyone</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> who is unable to demonstrate 1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2-month lawful residence in the UK.  This includes British people who have never had to prove their UK residence before and have no documentation to prove it, British people who are abroad, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">immigrants who have been lawfully in the UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">less than 12 m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">onths.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Children, mentally</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ill people, disabled people and any other categories of vulnerable persons</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> whose circumstances or cases do not fit into the narrow criteria of the “vulnerability” for which the exemptions are made</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  For example, a disabled pers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on with irregular immigration status will not be able to access civil legal aid to challenge a local authority’s decision to make him/her homeless even if it were to breach the person’s convention rights.  A victim of trafficking, if assaulted by the polic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e, will not be able to access civil legal aid to challenge the assault.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Cases whereby the state, the police and other publicly authorit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">abused, assaulted or otherwise ill treated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> people with irregular immigration status.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> allegation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of sexual abuse of women immigration detainees by security guards working at Yarl’s Wood Immigration Removal Centre, recently reported by the Observer, would not be within the scope of the civil legal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> aid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.      </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We also remain concerned about the access </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to justice </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">people who are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> detained under immigration powers in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">immigration detention centres</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> prisons</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is important to note that detention places individuals in an extremely vulnerable situation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as they have to be entirely dependent on those who </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">incarcerate them</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and at particular risk of human rights violations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In the UK, a considerable number of people with irregular immigration status find themselves in this situation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In 2012, a total of 28,909 people entered detention, the highest since t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he Coalition Government came into power in May 2010</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  On any given date, more than 2,000 people are held in immigration detention centres: at the end of 2012, there were 2,685 people detained in immigration detention centres</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, of which 1,676 (62%) were pe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ople who have claimed asylum at some point.  Although it is not possible to establish exactly how many of these have pending asylum claims and would be exempt from the proposed residence test, from our experience there remains significant number of irregul</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ar migrants who do not have any pending asylum claims.  Additionally, it was recently reported that there are almost 1,000 irregular migrants held in prisons under immigration power after they have completed their sentences</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  The scale of immigration dete</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ntion is also set to rise, following the ministerial statement made on 4 September 2013 that HMP The Verne would be converted into a 600-bed Immigration Removal Centre.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As mentioned earlier</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, the exceptions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to the residence test </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">do not cover cases of abu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ses and ill-treatment whilst people are in detention.  There will be no civil legal aid available to bring cases if they are harmed, assaulted or killed by the detention </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">centre personnel or during the process of removals or deportation.  Cases such as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">death of Jimmy Mubenga in 2010</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> during </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> removal process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, which was found to be unlawful killing following a lengthy inquest process,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> will not benefit from civil legal aid.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Additionally, there will be also no civil legal aid available for those who </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hav</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">detained unlawfully to seek compensation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> from the Home Office</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  From the information available, it appears that t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he Home Office paid out £3 million in 2008-09 and £12 million in 2009-10 in compensation and legal costs arising from unlawful detention</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> actions</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Removal of civil legal aid means that there will no longer any incentive for the Home Office to act lawfully</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and respect human rights of those in detention</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK’s immigration detention system also places individuals in this vulnerable positio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n for an extended period of time.  U</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nlike many other countries in Europe and the rest of the world, the UK does not have a time limit on immigration detention, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">resulting in many long-term detention cases. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Although the Joint Committee of Human Rights took t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he view in 2007 that 28 days of immigration detention would provide sufficient time to make removal arrangem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ents for refused asylum seekers</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, most people who enter the detention estate sp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">end much longer in detention.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Home Office snapshot on 31 Decembe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">r 2012 shows that over 68% of people who were in detention were detained longer than 29 days.  Of 2,685 people who were in detention on 31 December 20126, 68% (1832) were in detention longer than 29 days, 31% (822) were in detention longer than 3 months, 1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4% (375) were in detention longer than 6 months and 5% (134) had been in detention longer than one year</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.   </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">aware that a whole range of vulnerable people are regularly found in immigration detention.  They include people with serious mental h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ealth problems, trafficking victims, survivors of torture, gender violence and other human rights violation, pregnant women and unaccompanied minors.  LGBTI asylum seekers also find themselves in detention.  They are commonly survivors of sexual assault, r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ape or genital mutilation.  Detention can trigger secondary trauma, particularly where previous persecution included some form of incarceration.  Their identity also exposes them to risks of physical and verbal harassment in detention. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The residence test </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">will make it impossible for them to have a legal remedy against mistreatment whilst in detention.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Abuses and ill-treatment can happen regardless of the level of rigor with which independent monitoring is carried out or the presence of stringent statutory regulations and other rules which govern the practice of detention.  Although </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">complaints systems do</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> exist, people in immigration detention will inevitable face barriers in utilising such systems effectively due to their vulnerability, language barriers and other issues.  Likewise, it would be impossible or, at least, extremely difficult, for the same in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">dividuals to prepare and represent their cases, which fall outside the scope of the civil legal aid as a result of the proposed residence test, on their own. It is vital, therefore, that civil legal aid remains available to enable access to legal remedy wh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">en it is necessary – otherwise the state will be able to act with impunity against people with irregular immigration status.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Some people who leave detention, particularly those with support needs, need civil legal aid in order to secure access to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">appropriate accommodation and subsistence support in the community.  People held in immigration detention can access Section 4 bail addresses from the Home Office and these addresses are essential when applying for bail.  We are aware that the Home Office </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">frequently fail</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to provide addresses or delay</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> provision of address</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for many months.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Without civil legal aid, migrants in this situation will be unable to challenge these delays.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This, therefore, indirectly impacts on these individuals’ ability to sec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ure their liberty.    </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Section 4 accommodation and subsistence support is often unsuitable for those who suffer from mental or physical health problems </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are released into the community.   We are aware, however, that local authorities often dispute thei</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">r legal duty provide support to these individuals and specialist lawyers need to step in to instigate judicial review proceedings.  The residence test would make it impossible for such very vulnerable individuals in detention to legally challenge the local</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> authority’s decisions, and as a result, their detention might be prolonged</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> or they </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">might </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">face having to live in inadequate conditions which fall below the minimum human right standards.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> principle of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> equality of arms will not be maintained</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> once the r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">esidence test is introduced.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The state will continue to be represented by lawyers, at public expense, and affected individuals who represent themselves will be at a significant disadvantage in an adversarial legal system.  The proposed test, therefore, a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lso risks undermining fundamental human rights protected by our domestic law (Human Rights Act) and international obligations (e.g. European Convention on Human Rights). This includes the right to a fair trial and ensuring that all people have effective ac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cess the courts.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">L</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">egal aid is still available if </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">otherwise there</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">breach </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">individuals’ human rights under </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">exceptional funding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> scheme under s10 of the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ccording to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Public Law Project</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (PLP)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, this system is simply not working</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and offers no protection that the Ministry of Justice insists that it does</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In July </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">20</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">13, three months into the operation, the Legal Aid Agency has only received 233 such applications, of wh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ich only six were granted legal aid (and four of them inquest cases), while 5,000 applications </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">had</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> been initially expected between April </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">20</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">13 to March</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 20</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">14.  The PLP, who has been running a special project assisting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">people to appl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">y for exceptional funding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">says</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ‘Our experience is that the process of applying for exceptional funding is extremely onerous and that for litigants in person it is completely impenetrable: it requires the submission of a fourteen page form, complete with a detailed explanation of th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e client’s circumstances, and a valid means and merits form. For providers, this work is done at risk, with payment only being made if exceptional funding is granted. There is no mechanism for deciding cases on an emergency basis and there is no exemption </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for people who lack capacity to litigate. It is our experience that providers are routinely refusing to make exceptional funding applications because it is too time consuming and, as will be seen below, too risky. It is also our experience that the quality</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of decision-making by the Legal Aid Agency in these cases is very poor.’</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are also concerned that, while the proposals are made in an attempt to reduce overall public spending,  the Ministry of Justice fails to consider fully other additional costs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that could be incurred as a result of reducing the legal aid costs (although no cost</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">savings figure is provided for at all in the case of the proposed residence test).   For instance, the judiciary is likely to experience additional costs as a result of an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> increase in the number of self-representing “litigants in person” at the court, as the judges and the court services are likely to need to spend more time handling these cases.  Inappropriate cases could be started by “litigants in person” who were not ab</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">le to access legal advice which would have advised them not to proceed with the cases: all areas of law are extremely complex and it is not reasonable to expect un-trained individuals to competently navigate the legal system unaided.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In the context of t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he residence test, costs to providers for establishing immigration status are not calculated by the Ministry of Justice.  According to the calculation made by Dr Nick Armstrong, a barrister at Garden Court Chambers, it will cost at least £2.6 million</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  No</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Recourse to Public Fund Network estimates that there is likely to be additional £26m expenditure to the local authorities as a result of the residence test, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to cover the costs increased</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in homelessness among people with no</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> recourse to public funds and pay</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing legal costs for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> children </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with irregular immigration status </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">supported by the local</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">authority</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">On the other hand, no estimated figure for the cost savings as a result of introducing the residence test has been provided by the Ministry of Justice.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lso oppose the introduction of a residence test on the grounds that it is entirely unworkable.  It will force legal practitioners who are not immigration specialists to gain immigration law expertise simply in order for them to be able to carry out the res</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">idence test.  As many immigration practitioners can testify, establishing whether </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">someone is lawfully resident in the UK or not, or how long the person has been / was lawfully resident in the UK or not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> could be a rather complicated legal matter, which may</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in itself need specialist legal advice and assistance to resolve.  There is no single document or stamp that indicates the person’s lawful residence in the UK.  Even if here was some form of evidence in one’s passport, that passport could be with the Home</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Office because of a pending immigration claim.  Some people simply do not have such a document because the law allows their residence without having to make an application of any kind.   </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are also alarmed that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the proposals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, including those concerning</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> judicial review, w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hich have such huge constitutional implications, are to be implemented through secondary legislation, without the full parliamentary scrutiny afforded to primary legislation.   </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In conclusion, we urge the Committee to seek</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> evidence from the Ministry of Justice as to how the proposed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">residence test will not have impact on access to justice, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">will</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not undermine the rule of law and will not incur any additional costs elsewhere.  In our view, we believe that the residence test s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hould be rejected altogether give</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">human rights and other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">concerns highlighted</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">v</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">27 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">6</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> As detailed in Annex B of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Transforming Legal Aid: Next steps</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.londonspovertyprofile.org.uk/indicators/topics/londons-geography-population/londons-hidden-population/"><span style="color:#0563c1; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.londonspovertyprofile.org.uk/indicators/topics/londons-geography-population/londons-hidden-population/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Data tables Immigration Statistics October – December 2012 Volume 1, see table dt.01  The numbers denote those entering Immigration Remo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">val Centres and Short Term Holding Facilities and are held solely under Immigration Act powers.  They exclude those in police cells, Prison Service establishments, short term holding rooms at ports and airports for less than 24 hours, and those recorded as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> detained under both criminal and immigration powers and their dependants. http://www.homeoffice.gov.uk/publications/science-research-statistics/research-statistics/immigration- asylum-research/immigration-tabs-q4-2012/?view=Standard&amp;pubID=1156263   </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Dat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">a tables Immigration Statistics October – December 